	doi = {10.1088/0004-637X/749/1/92},
	abstract = {Tidal disruption of main-sequence stars by black holes has generally been thought to lead to a signal dominated by {UV} emission. If, however, the black hole spins rapidly and the poloidal magnetic ﬁeld intensity on the black hole horizon is comparable to the inner accretion disk pressure, a powerful jet may form whose luminosity can easily exceed the thermal {UV} luminosity. When the jet beam points at Earth, its non-thermal luminosity can dominate the emitted spectrum. The thermal and non-thermal components decay differently with time. In particular, the thermal emission should remain roughly constant for a signiﬁcant time after the period of maximum accretion, beginning to diminish only after a delay, whereas after the peak accretion rate, the non-thermal jet emission decays, but then reaches a plateau. Both transitions are tied to a characteristic timescale {tEdd} at which the accretion rate falls below Eddington. Making use of this timescale in a new parameter-inference formalism for tidal disruption events with signiﬁcant emission from a jet, we analyze the recent ﬂare source Swift J2058. It is consistent with an event in which a main-sequence solar-type star is disrupted by a black hole of mass ∼ 4 × 107 M . The beginning of the ﬂat phase in the non-thermal emission from this source can possibly be seen in the late-time light curve. Optical photometry over the ﬁrst 40 days of this ﬂare is also consistent with this picture, but is only weakly constraining because the bolometric correction is very uncertain. We suggest that future searches for main-sequence tidal disruptions use methods sensitive to jet radiation as well as to thermal {UV} radiation.},
